    <section class="section">
      <h2>Who I am</h2>
      <p>
        I work on public mechanics — the discipline of how technology and services actually
        reach the people governments are supposed to serve. The practice sits at the intersection
        of service design, infrastructure studies, political economy, and critical technology.
      </p>
      <p>
        For two decades I have advised executives across U.S. higher education, state and local
        government, federal cabinet agencies, and international institutions. I led design at 18F,
        taught service design at the University of Michigan, and ran the digital practice for the
        City of Bloomington.
      </p>
      <p>
        With air cover I work in days or weeks. Without it I work in months or years. I take a
        small number of engagements a year and am deliberately not a studio.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <h2>What I am working on</h2>
      <p>
        The argument underneath the current work: fifteen years into U.S. civic technology,
        government delivery has not meaningfully improved. Vendor dependency persists. Technologists
        are still treated as external capacity. The AI moment will accelerate that dependency if it
        is not redirected.
      </p>
      <p>
        The position I am developing in response is that the role of technology in public services
        is to absorb the ninety-percent case so human judgment can be applied at the edge — and that
        the difference between U.S. delivery and the international models I take seriously is whether
        the system defaults to yes or defaults to no.
      </p>
      <p>
        State Capacity AI is the research and practice arm of that argument. AI systems are already
        determining benefits, housing, and access. There is no shared standard for disclosure, no
        common vocabulary for what authority a system holds, and no usable mechanism to contest a
        decision made by software. I am building a decision-authority taxonomy, disclosure language,
        and contestability patterns intended to travel into procurement and policy.
      </p>
      <p>
        On open infrastructure I work on a small suite of projects on the AT Protocol — Glowrm for
        portable trust, HeyPBJ for structured matching, Leafroll for professional identity that does
        not fit into a résumé.
      </p>
      <p>
        In 2025 I founded Portland Digital Corps, a volunteer practice that organised more than fifty
        practitioners to deliver six nonprofit websites in eight-week engagements without procurement
        or institutional cover. The model has been adopted in other cities. My continued involvement
        is to hold the door open.
      </p>
      <p>
        Longer-form writing is collected at <a href="https://makingpublicwork.com">makingpublicwork.com</a>.
      </p>

