    <section class="section">
      <h2>Where I can help</h2>
      <p>
        The clearest way to describe the practice is to describe the situations in which executives
        bring me in.
      </p>
      <p>
        A service is being delivered inside binding constraints. Policy that cannot be changed,
        legacy systems that cannot be replaced, a delivery date that is not moving. The need is for
        someone who has worked inside this kind of room before, can identify the failure states
        quickly, and can leave the team with patterns that survive contact with the operating
        environment.
      </p>
      <p>
        An AI system is being stood up, or being asked to be governed, in a high-stakes context.
        Benefits, eligibility, screening, triage, child welfare. The need is for disclosure language,
        contestability mechanics, a taxonomy of what the system is actually doing, and a register in
        which procurement, legal, and front-line staff can have the same conversation.
      </p>
      <p>
        An institution is building on open protocols. Two years on AT Protocol. For identity, trust,
        matching, moderation, portable reputation, or anything that needs to live across networks
        rather than inside a single platform, I can engage on the data model, the consent surface,
        and the social mechanics — not only the interface.
      </p>
      <p>
        A design function needs leadership for a defined period. Fractional head of design, interim
        design lead, or the leadership of a specific programme. I have led teams at federal scale and
        in city government and am comfortable with the political and operational dimensions of the
        role.
      </p>
      <p>
        I am not the appropriate engagement for brand or marketing work, growth-led product design,
        consumer applications whose economics depend on attention capture, or work whose primary
        deliverable is a slide document.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <h2>How I work</h2>
      <p>
        I work inside constraints, not around them. Policy tends to be policy. Legacy tends to be
        legacy. The leverage available to design is in how decisions are made, communicated, and
        recovered from when they fail.
      </p>
      <p>
        I optimise for recoverability over polish. In high-stakes services the failure mode that
        matters is not a rough happy path; it is a dead end with no route back. Most of my design
        time is spent on the moments where people get stuck, abandon, or receive a determination
        they cannot contest.
      </p>
      <p>
        I write things down. Decisions, vocabularies, the reasoning behind a pattern. The durable
        value I have left inside organisations has rarely been a design file. It has been a shared
        language teams could use to argue about service mechanics without bikeshedding the interface.
      </p>
      <p>
        I prefer defined engagements with clear outputs. Eight to twelve weeks is the usable range
        for delivery work. For ongoing advisory I commit a half-day a week and write a memo at the
        end of each month.
      </p>
      <p>
        I am not running a studio. The engagement is with me. Where a project genuinely requires a
        team I will say so and help assemble or refer one.
      </p>
    </section>

